    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-09-23T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-09-23T01:00:00-05:00" n="45"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d45">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/1847: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-23T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >September 23, 1931—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 23—10:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>632. Following unsigned but apparently from American Consul at Mukden: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“September 22, 9 a.m. Civil government in Mukden in process of
                            organization along the following lines: Mayor will be a Japanese; the
                            principal municipal departments will be under the joint control of
                            Japanese and Chinese chiefs; all subordinate positions will be filled by
                            Chinese. Doihara, formerly in Kuantung army, is to be Mayor of Mukden.
                            Difficulty is being experienced in securing Chinese willing to
                            participate. It is planned to have similar municipal governments in
                            Antung, Newchwang, Changchun, Ssupingkai, and Kirin.</p>
                        <p>Occupation of Kirin city by Japanese was completed yesterday and the
                            Chientao area is being similarly occupied. Japanese do not intend to
                            send troops to Taonan and the Hsingan area, at least for the time
                            being.</p>
                        <p>As all Chinese soldiers have moved out, the maintenance of order at
                            Huangkutung, the present terminus of the Peiping-Mukden Railway, will
                            probably necessitate Japanese occupation today or tomorrow.</p>
                        <p>Regular Japanese troops in occupation of Manchuria now number
                            approximately 16,000, not including military police, train guards and
                            civilian reserves under arms.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
